1207 // strongSIVtest -
1208 // From the paper, Practical Dependence Testing, Section 4.2.1
1209 //
1210 // When we have a pair of subscripts of the form [c1 + a*i] and [c2 + a*i],
1211 // where i is an induction variable, c1 and c2 are loop invariant,
1212 //  and a is a constant, we can solve it exactly using the Strong SIV test.
1213 //
1214 // Can prove independence. Failing that, can compute distance (and direction).
1215 // In the presence of symbolic terms, we can sometimes make progress.
1216 //
1217 // If there's a dependence,
1218 //
1219 //    c1 + a*i = c2 + a*i'
1220 //
1221 // The dependence distance is
1222 //
1223 //    d = i' - i = (c1 - c2)/a
1224 //
1225 // A dependence only exists if d is an integer and abs(d) <= U, where U is the
1226 // loop's upper bound. If a dependence exists, the dependence direction is
1227 // defined as
1228 //
1229 //                { < if d > 0
1230 //    direction = { = if d = 0
1231 //                { > if d < 0
1232 //
1233 // Return true if dependence disproved.
1234 bool DependenceInfo::strongSIVtest(const SCEVAddRecExpr *Src,
